Description: Very small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a small concave surface with organic impression (wood or leather?). In the break two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm. The upper side is slightly convex with some finger imprints next to the seal. The lower two thirds of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible on the top. Recognisable are two stylized standing figures holding a staff between them. The figure on the left is probably Re-Harakhte and the one on the right Amun. Both are positioned on top of a standing line. The same motif can be found on EA86902 and EA86911. The style is very similar to the motif of EA86792, EA86793, EA86799, EA86800, EA86801, EA86802 and EA86812.
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
